// save that block number
// declare a uint8_t pointer called ptr and set it data[block_number][remainder]

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;

// declare a uint8_t pointer called ptr and set it data[block_number][remainder]
uint8_t * ptr = &data[startingBlock][remainder];
// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}

// loop and print the number of bytes

for(int j = 0;j<numBytes;j++)
{
    printf(" 0x%x\n",*ptr);
    ptr++;
}
